This is a decision log — an append-only record of non-obvious choices and rejected alternatives. It is consumed as a reference on design questions and serves as the authoritative narrative for why the system's architecture is the way it is.

Each entry documents a single resolved decision: the context that prompted it, the choice made, rejected alternatives with their tradeoffs, and the rationale. Entries are never rewritten (superseded by a new ADR instead). The log is discoverable and read on demand — it is not summarized into the tree.

The entries cover the full span of the project: the Rust lint/test regime (Layer 1), the context summarization pipeline and its prompt design, the reference meal-planner project, the environmental sandbox for agent runs, and the user-facing tools. Early ADRs (001–005) established the sealed-spec discipline and foundational choices; later ones document the pivot from top-down enforcement (cage-based source masking) to opt-in context injection (via Claude Code hooks), the reconciliation and freshness mechanisms for the summary tree, and the model-choice and cage-config refactorings that flowed from that pivot.